{"/service/ndnp/ohi/batch_ohi_goyle_ver01/data/sn82007637/00516993832/1958053001/0288.xml":{"full_text":"President Warns of Inflation\nTax Reduction Held Doomed\nBy Ike\u2019s View Of Recession\nPres. Eisenhower is convinced that the recession has\nbeen licked and that the nation now must be mobilized for\nan all out attack on a \u201cjust-around-the-corner\u201d inflation.\nAgainst a backdrop of 5.2 million unemployed workers\nand a continuing drop in industrial production and wage and\nsalary income, the Presidents\ntold 2,600 business leaders\nthat the nation's worst post\nwar recession is slowing down\nafter nine months and that an\neconomic upturn is \u201cin the mak\ning.\"\nHe called on labor to forego\nwage increases that would af\nfect a \"stable dollar\" and urged\nbusiness to be chary of price\nboosts.\nshift\nof\nThe President's\nemphasis from the necessity\nfor battling the severe eco\nnomic slump to worry about\na possible inflation in the fu\nture virtually ruled out any\nindications of a reduction in\nincome taxes for low and mod\nerate income families, a key\nweapon urged by labor to put\nthe nation back on the recov\nery road.\nThe President's speech to a\nmobilization conference of the\nAmerican Management Associa-i\ntion came about 48 hours before\nthe Labor Dept, released figures\nshowing living costs rising to\nanother all-time record high.\nThe Bureau of Labor Statis\ntics reported that living costs\nrose two-tenths of one percent\nfrom mid-April to mid-May to\n123.5, or 3.5 percent higher than\na year ago.\nThe index has gone up in\n18 of the past 20 months and\nwas unchanged in the other\ntwo months. The last decline\nwas registered in August 1956.\nThe latest rise means a cost\nof-living increase of 2 cents an\nhour for about 250,000 workers\nin farm implements and auto\nparts and 3 cents an hour for\nabout 180,000 other workers.\nLikened to Hoover\nEwan Clague, commissioner\nof labor statistics, said he was\nnot including the Auto Workers\nat the \"big three\u201d firms be\ncause their contracts expire at\nthe end of the month.\nSen. Paul H. Douglas (D-III\nrenewing his demand for an im\nmediate income tax cut, said\nPres. Eisenhower's speech\nwas\ncomparable to Herbert Hoover\u2019s\nprediction of 28 years ago that\nCity Council\n(Continued from Page 1)\nincreased 75 cents effected July]\n1, and again 50 cents next Jan. 1\nIn addition longevity increases\nwould be given as follows: $100\na year to employees with 15 or\nmore years continuous service\neffective July 1; $100 to em\nployees with 10 to 14 years serv\nice, effective next Jan 1. and\n(150 to employees with 15 or\nmore years continuous service,\neffective next Jan. 1\nFor the final six months of\nthis year the raises would cost\nthe city $311,073. For the full\nyear of 1050, the city would\nhave to pay out another $954,\n530\nSenators invited\nTo CWA Convention\nThe Communications Workers\nhave invited the seven members\nof the Kennedy Senate Labor\nsubcommittee to attend \u201call or\nany part\" of the union's Miami\nBeach convention June 9-13 to\n\u201csee how democracy prevails.\"\n\u201cOur conventions are a true\nreflection of the attitudes of our\nmetiers and the decisions rep\nresent the will of the rank-and\nfll delegates.\" CWA Pres. Joseph\nA Beirne said in announcing the\ninvitations.\nTOLEDO UNION\nJOURNAL\nTrading Post\nKaUit 40 cent* a lint (5 uordi), minimum 2 linn, 80\ncenlt. Hail with cath or bring in to Room 203, 245 W in\nthrop Street, CH. 1-9126, Extention 33.\nFuneral Directors\nDAY-EDWARDS MORTUARY\n741 W. Central Ave.\nCH 4-0751\nHOEFLINGER MORTUARY\nSOI PUtt at\nOX 1-6768\nFOTH MORTUARY\nM10 Jefferson Ave\nCH 1-3241\nABELE FUNERAL HOME\n1910 Cherry St\nCH 3-0101\nPARKS D EMMERT FUNERAL HOME\n8883 Monroe St.\nGR 3-3110\nH H. BIRKENKAMP FUNERAL\nHOMES\u20141003 Broadway\nTRILBY. Ohio. GR 4-3773\nCH 3-3103\nBROWN FUNERAL HOME\n*1* Grand Ave\nCH 3-0433\nTelevision Sett\nTV SET Home appliances all types\n1854 W Central Ave\nHardware Supplier\nPAITS all kinds, low prices Colon\nial Hardware 1854 Central\n\"prosperity is just around the\ncorner.\"\nThe President's opposition to\ntax cuts, reinforced in a speech\nby Vice Pres. Nixon to the same\nbusiness meeting, was reflected\nin Congress by predictions that\nat best there might be some re\nductions in excises and aid for\nsmall business but little hope for\nincome tax cuts.\nThe high-inflation pitch of the\nPresident's speech was indicat\ned earlier in an address by Bud\nget Dir. Maurice Stans in which\nhe warned of a budgetary deficit\nof from $8 to $10 billion in the\nfiscal year starting July 1, in\naddition to the $3 billion now\nanticipated for the current fiscal\nyear. He strongly opposed any\nactions which would add to \"fu\nture burdens.\u201d\nLeon H. Keyserling, chair\nman of the Council of Eco\nnomic Advisers in the Truman\nAdministrations, told a con\ngressional committee, h o w\never, that a $9 billion increase\nin government spending is\nneeded to stimulate economic\nexpansion.\nThe current recession, he said.\n1\nAll-Out Senate Fight i\nLooms on Jobless Pay\nA bipartisan coalition is girding for an all-out Senate\nfloor fight to force improvements in the pending emergency\njobless pay bill. After beating down a move by Sen. Paul H.\nDouglas (D-Ill.) to liberalize its provisions, the Senate Bank\ning Committee, under the chairmanship of Sen. Harry F. i\nByrd (D-Va.), reported out a\nbill similar to the watered\ndown Administration meas\nure passed by the House. The'\ncommittee vote was 11 to 4.\nEarly this month. Labor\nSec. James P. Mitchell said\nin Chicago that he would ask\nthe Senate to substitute the\nAdministration measure for\nthe House-approved bill, de-\ndaring \"the federally-financed\nplan proposed by the Presi\ndent is best.\"\nEight days later, he ap\npeared before Byrd's commit\ntee to testify that the emas\nculated version of the White\nHouse\nbill\n_ _ is acceptable to\n1 the Administration.\"\nQueried on the reversal, a La\nbor Dept, spokesman said that\nin the interim \u201cthe Administra\ntion\u201d had decided \u201cwe had bet\nter take what we could get.\u201d\nThe original Mitchell plan\nthough criticized by liberals and\nlabor spokesmen, made payment\nof emergency benefits to jobless\nworkers mandatory.\nBipartisan Fight Planned\nThe floor fight to improve\nthe measure will be led by Sena\ntors Douglas, John F. Kennedy\n(D-Mass.), Jacob K. Javits (R\nN. V.) and others in a biparti\nsan group.\nCharging that the diluted\nmeasure \u201cgives the appear\nance of action without the\ni substance of action,\" Kennedy\nurged the Byrd committee to\nsubstitute his basic bill pro\nvidIng federal standards ex\ntending the benefit period,\nboosting the size of benefits\nand broadening coverage to\ninclude millions currently ex\ncluded.\nKennedy warned the commit\ntee that if it reported the House\n[measure lie would carry his own\nversion to the Senate floor. Lib\nerals also are expected to offer\nService\nGERBER CABINET 8HOP\u2014Specialist\nin kitchen remodeling CH 2-9337\nPAY water. gas, phone. light bills at\nLocal 12 dues window\nMail your Sales Tax Stamps to F\nReno. 425 Winthrop St\nNEW YORK Life Insurance Co. Rich\nard C Duffey Agent CH 8-6481\nHall For Rent\u2014Kitchen facilities. 3015\nDetroit near Central CH fl-4806\nCall Huber Brothers Union Band for\nyour next dance. WA. 8877.\nMiscellaneous\nFOR SALE: McGuffeys\nEclectic\nSpeller Call Grand Rapids 21137\ni WILL TRADE $150 automatic washer\nfor small boat and motor LU. 4-6930\nSinger Portable Sewing Machine with\nforward and reverse, $35. WA. 9607.\nFOR SALE: 4-Room Cottage. Harbor\nView. Asking $1700 cash. CH. 6-8493.\nDOMESTIC SEWING SERVICE\u2014Sew\ning Machine and Vacuum Cleaners\nSpecialists, WA. 9607.\nIt thert tomething you no longer need and would like\nto give away to help tome other union member? Jutl call\nL our. uGitt i.way Column,** CHerry 1*9126, Ext. 33.\nt\nis \"merely the latest phase of a\nlong-term retreat from a neces\nsary rate of economic growth\nsince the end of the Korean\nwar.\u201d He added:\n\"If we are satisfied merely\nwith a leveling off of the reces\nsion we shall continue to\nsuffer a very high level of chron\nic unemployment and face with\nin a few short years a recession\neven more serious than this one.\u201d\nRelief Problems Rising\nOn the economic front, mean\nwhile, there were predictions\nthat about 2.6 million workers'\nwould exhause their unemploy-j\nment compensation benefits this\nyear with a sharp increase due\nin June and July. In April ex-|\nhaustions reached 230,000 ere\na ting serious problems for re- i\nlief and welfare agencies.\nl\nPeter T. Schoermann, presi-\ndent of the Plumbers and Pipe I\nFitters, told the Mechanical\nContractors A s s o c i ation of\nAmerica that figures on build\ning and construction indicate\nno assurance \"that the con\nstruction industry will save us\nfrom economic decline.\u201d\nAs compared with the first\nquarter of 1957, the first three\nmonths of this year shows every\nkind of construction award ex\nvept sewage and public build\ning slumping \u201cvery severely,\"\nSchoemann said\na series of amendments to im\nprove jobless benefits in specific\nareas.\nFinance\nStates Are Polled\nDouglas led the fight in the\nCommittee\nto\nwrite\nstronger legislation. In a poll of\nstate governors he had gathered\nevidence to show that in 90 per\ncent of the states constitutional\namendments or special legisla\ntive action would be needed be-l\nfore the period of paying bene-1\nfits could be extended under the\nvoluntary provisions of the'\nmeasure.\nWith 32 states replying to\ndate, only two governors said\nthey had clear-cut authority\nI\nto accept the federal advances.\nFive others were doubtful as\nto their ability to take action,\nand 25 others flatly reported\nthey required either amend\nments to their constitutions or\napproval of their legislatures.\nJavits told Byrd's committee\nthat the House-passed bill was'\nworthless because it did not re\nquire states to participate. Going'\nfar beyond the provisions of the\nbill which the Administration\nabandoned, Javits supported fed\neral standards that would wipe\nout present inequities existing\nunder varying state laws.\nWilliam L. Batt, Jr., Penn\nsylvania secretary of labor and\nindustry, testifying in behalf of\nDemocratic Gov. George M.\nLeader, attacked the House bill\nas a \"piece-meal\" measure and\nurged Congress to establish uni\nnational\nfor\nstandards\nform\nminimum benefits and length of\npayments.\nAlso supporting the Kennedy\nposition, in addition to the AFL\nCIO, were Sen. Albert Gore\n(D-Tenn.), the National Associa\ntion of Social Workers and the\nNational Conference of Catholic\nCharities, whose spokesmen tes\ntified in the wind-up to the com\nmittee's hearings.\n&sif\n1408.*\n\n01/\nWEICOMS DELEGATES\n.2 BIENNIAL CONVENTION\nAMALGAMATED CLOTHING WORKERS OF AMERICA\nAFL-CIO\n\n4\ni.\n*fs\nP\nADesrin\n12\nrs\n\n\n2)9 l5l\nauuad\nt* 9561,\nwmWMKO 1\n5\nW\n\nth\nSrs\n8\ni\n\n&s\n\n5.5\ns\n1\nLi\n3... .*S/5.0\n4s\nFe\n'1\nses\n(mW\none\n\nkamonke theFEAR\nteDATICN e\nwett oawZ\u00a3,t\nTeM\ns'\n\n.39\nEnlouart Phyi\nSaneto Onanamr.3\ngvrtnpn.\n1\nns*\nI\nnt\ntna\ni 4\nJ\ne\n*i\nto)\nft\nV*\nA\nff t\nw,*s f\nJa\" 4\n136,\nmceookggoo).\nMR\n8:\n3\nLata a.\nNEW SOUTHERN LOCALS set the tone for organizational activities by the Amalgamated Clothing\nWorkers during the next two years. Members of the locals stage an enthusiastic demonstration at\nthe union's 21st biennial convention in Atlantic City. The union. encouraged by organizational ac\ntivities which added 17,500 new members since the ACWA\u2019s 1956 convention, pledged renewed\nefforts.\nOhio Special Legislature Urged\nTo Improve UC Law For Good\nThe Executive Board of the newly-merged Ohio AFL\nCIO has recommended that the Special Session of the State\nLegislature improve the state\u2019s unemployment compensa\ntion law on a permanent basis rather than on a \u201ctemporary,\nstop-gap\u201d basis.\n\u201cThe present recession has\nagain underscored the short\ncomings of the present law,\u201d\nthe Board's statement asserted.\n\"Therefore, the Legislature\nshould modernize the law by\nproviding for more liberal week\nly payments over a longer per\niod and making such improve\nments on a permanent basis.\u201d\nThe legislative recommenda\ntions were reached May 26 at\nthe first meeting of the Ohio\nAFL-CIO's Executive Board\nsince the May fl merger conven\ntion in Cleveland. The Board is\nmade up of 24 vice presidents,\nplus the three top officers of the\nmerged state organization.\n75% Jobless Benefits Needed\nThe Board recommended that\nthe present law be changed per\nmanently so that the maximum\nweekly benefit equals 75% of\nthe industrial worker's average\nweekly wage. The Board also\nrecommended that the duration\nperiod be increased from the\npresent 26 weeks to 39 weeks.\nGov. C. William O\u2019Neill has\nannounced that he will ask the\nSpecial Session to lengthen the\npayment period to 39 weeks on a\ntemporary basis.\n\u201cThere is no doubt that the\npresent law simply cannot meet\nthe needs of the unemployed\nduring a period of sustained job\nlessness,\" the AFL-CIO Board\nsaid.\nCommunity Chest\nNames 4 UAW Men\nTo Budget Group\nRobert L. Knight, chairman,\nhas named Derele Collins, Char\nlee J. Clark, Harold J. Mouch\nand James Crowley of the UAW\nto the important Budget Com\nmittee of the Greater Toledo\nCommunity Chest.\nThis 6 0-person Committee\nthrough Sub-Committees. will\nbe meeting during the next few\nmonths with representatives of\nthe fifty-six Red Feather Agen\ncies to discuss Budget needs\nand\ndetermine\nallocations of\nCommunity Chest Funds.\nCharles Clark is also a Cheat\nboard member and Jack Thomp\nson is on the Chest staff.\nAuthorised Repair Service for\nNorelco Electric Shavers\nSmall Electric Appliances\nGeneral Repair Equipment\n116 SUMMIT ST. CH. 3-1431\n0\nAUTO\nSERMCE\nNo! No! That's not the way to open a clogged gas line\nt*\nGAS\nI\nHerb\u2019s Gulf Service\nCOLLINGWOOD at ASHLAND\nCH. -0432\nIX\nt\nClem\u2019s Marathon Service\nDETROIT at PHILLIPS\nGR. 2-0342\nMiller\u2019s Pure Oil Service\nBERDAN at HAVERHILL\nGR. 5-7581\nRay Lentz Sohio Service\nI EARING at DUNHAM\nWA. PI73\n\u201cChanging the law on a tem\nporary. stop-gap basis w>u not\nsolve the problem. it will only\nsweep it under the rug.\nThe Board said it was in\nhuman for the state to expect the\nfamily of a jobless worker to\nlive on $36 or $39 a week and\nstop even these meager\nhuman\nto Sup\namounts after 26 weeks if new\nwork has not been found.'\n\u201cOrganised Labor has main\ntained for many years that the\nOhio law is sadly outdated, the\nBoard said. \u201cIt is time to face\nthe issue and bring it up to\ndate.\u201d\nThe Board reaffirmed Labor s\ncontention that the present un\nemployment compensation law\npermits the payment of supple\nmental unemployment benefits\n(SUB) in addition to state com\npensation._\nOfficers Named\nBy Toledo Typos\nToledo Typographical Union\nlast week held its annual elec\ntion for local officers. They also\nballoted on international offi\ncers, and on a proposed amend\nment to the constitution of ITU.\nElected locally for the 1958\n59 term of office were the fol\nlowing:\nTroutman, president;\nLester\nJohn Nowak, vice-president,\nRichard Cartwright, recording\nsecretary; Henry Thebes secre\ntary-treasurer; Robert Downs,\nreading clerk; Warren Cooper,\nbusiness representative; Mitchell\nMyers, sergeant-at-arms.\n.__ a: Pg A\nBoard of directors. Arthur\nReape, Ralph Sparks, Eugene\nDavis Howard Radcliffe and\nThomas Dooley; apprentice com\nmittee: Mr. Davis, Thomas Cald\nwell, Lionel Little, Robert Mc\nKeown and Olon Thompson; de\nlegates to Allied Printing Trades\nCouncil: Mr. Cooper, Mr. Trout\nman and Mr. Caldwell, auditing\ncommittee: Wilhelm Schmidt.\nGerald Momsen and Edward\nSund; delegates to Toledo Cen\ntral Labor Union: Mr. Cooper,\nMr. Reape, Otto Bryant, Mr.\nMcKeown and Mr. Nowak _\nArbitration committee. K\nDavis and Mr. Nowak; sanitary\ncommittee: Mr. McKeown, Mr\nLittle\ngates\n\u2022\u2022\u2022t JI\nand Elmo Collins; dele\nOhio Typographical\nto\nConference: Mr Radcliffe and\nMr. Little; delegate to ITU con\nvention: Mr. Thebes; alternate\nivenuvM. _-.\ndelegate: Mr. Sparks.\nBenevolent feeling ennobles\nthe most trifling actions.\nMakepeace Thackeray^\nI\nNo Aid Seen\nComing From\nOhio Solons\ni\nTwo Ohio legislators from To\nledo have questioned whether\nGov. C. William O'Neill and the\nRepublican leadership of the\nOhio Legislature really intend\nto do anything meaningful to\nhelp the jobless at the special\nsession next month.\nNoting the statements made\nby the Governor and the leaders\nof the Ohio Senate and House,\nState Sen. Frank W. King of\nToledo and Rep. Francis Reno\ndeclared:\n\u201cTaking the statements of all\nthree it can only be concluded\nthat it is the usual double talk\nwith no real intention of doing\nanything substantial for the un\nemployed workers in the State\nof Ohio unless they are forced\nto either by an- Act of Congress\nor the will of the people.\u201d\nThe Governor; the president\nof the Ohio Senate, C. Stanley\nMechem, and the Speaker of the\nOhio Assembly, Roger Cloud,\nare on record for providing only\ntemporary relief to Ohio\u2019s job\nI less and against rewriting the\nlaw to allow SUB.\nSenator King and Representa\ntive Reno also pointed out that\nthe Governor has issued con\nflicting statements on aiding the\njobless.\n\u201cOn one hand the Governor\nsays he will brook no interfer\nence from the Federal Govern\njment on this matter,\u201d the two\nToledoans pointed out.\n\u201cOn the other the Governor\nsays he will await the action of\nCongress before setting a specific\ni\ndate for the Special Session.\n\u201cIn view of these statements\nit is hard for us to understand\nwhat he and the leadership of\nthe Legislature actually mean.\u201d\nGenuine benevolence is not\nstationary, but peripatetic; it\ngoes about doing good.\n\u2014William Nevins\nWhere there is the most love\nto God, there will be there the\ntruest and most enlarged philan\nI\nthropy.\n\u2014Robert Southey\nIf\no BECKMANN OPTICAL CO.\nwe Established 1874\nw Oldest Optical Company\nw in Toledo\nIt MINKE, OPTOMETRIT\nPhone CH. 3-5512\nIts Edward Lamb Bidg.\nDiSalle\nPlating Co., Inc.\n28SI South St.\nWA 3473\nDON'T WORRY ABOUT RAIN\u2014DRIVE A CLEAN CAR\nTour Car Wash\nGuaranteed\nAgainst Rain\nTill Midnight\nOr We\nRe-Wash It\nThe Next Day\nFREE!\nRAIN\nCHECE\nOPEN DAILY\nSAJI lo 6 P.M.\nClosed Sundays\nand Holidays\nWHILI-U-WAIT\u201410 MINUTES OR LESS\nJefferson at 20th\u2014Thur-O-Auto Wash, Inc.\nUNDERCOATING\nALL\nCARS\nComplete Undercoating, including Hood,\nFenders. Gas Tank and Underbody\nWe use the finest undercoating material\navailable. Guaranteed. Steam cleaning\n$17\nTOLEDO UNDERCOATING CO.\nOpen 8-6 Monday Through Saturday\n4544 Monroe St. (Near Secor Rd.) New Exchange GR. 5-1811\n1\nFamily Savings Held\niStatistical Mirage\n9\nA \u201cstatistical mirage\u201d of an overflowing reservoir of\nsavings that can be tapped to spur economic recovery is be\ning used to mislead the public, the AFL-CIO Labor\u2019s Eco\nnomic Review charged. In its May issue, \u201cCan Family Sav\nings Recharge the Boom?\u201d the Review declared that a sue\ncessful attack on the cur\nrent business slump can be\nlaunched only \u201cby facing re\nalities squarely and not by\nburying our heads in statistical\nsands.\"\nThe realities, said the Review,\nare that:\nThe average skilled and\nsemi-skilled worker early in\n1957 had $212 in liquid per- i\nsonal savings and 26 percent\nof this group had none at all.\nThe average for unskilled or\nservice workers was $6, with\n49.5 percent having no sav\nings.\nOne-tenth V of all families\nown about two-thirds of all\nliquid personal savings.\nThe additional realities are.\nsaid\nthe\nReview,\nthat while\nAmericans possess an \"unprece\ndented accumulation of finan\ncial assets,\" they are not by a\nlong shot all \u201cspendable\" sav\nings.\nBreakdown Given\nThe total \u201csavings\" figure in\ncludes the following:\n1\u2014Billions of assets belong\nto thousands of non-profit or-\nganizations and over 3 million\nunincorporated businesses.\n2\u2014Tremendous accumulations\nof private and government in\nsurance and pension reserves,\nand welfare funds are count-1\ned in.\ni\n3\u2014Additional billions in cash\nand checking accounts also are\nincluded, although much of it is,\nin the process of being spent to'\nmeet daily needs.\n4\u2014A small minority of fam\nilies hold the vast bulk of the\nassets and savings. At the be\nginning of 1958 about 18 mil\nlion of the total of 57 million\ni families owned only from $1\nto $499 and another $4 million\nfamilies owned none.\ni 5\u2014Only 11 percent of all fam\nilies owned marketable securi\nties and most of them belong to\n1 the wealthiest one percent at the:\ntop.\n6\u2014\u201cThe current alleged sav\nings speedup is a bitter taunt to\nthe majority-of American fam-:\nilies. The millions now touched\nby unemployment and short\nworkweeks are, in fact, \u2018dissav\ners\u2019\u2014they are drawing upon\npast savings and going further\ninto debt.\u201d\nMust Pare Total\nI\nThe above conclusions, said\nthe Review, are based on gov\nernment statistics which show\nthat \"the towering mountain of\nso-called individual savings must\nbe pared down by two-thirds or\nmore if we want to guage ac\ncurately what really is available\nfor immediate family spending.\u201d\nIn addition. the Dept, of\nResearch publication said,\n\u201cwhile spendable savings of\nfamilies are non-existent or\nshockingly small, the indebt\nedness of many of these same\nfamilies has become a major\nproblem.\u201d\nI It would be a major disaster if;\nthe Administration and Congress'\nfell back on the savings theory j\nto check the recession. The an\nswer, said the Review lies in a\ntax cut for low and moderate\nincome families, extended and\nimproved unemployment com\npensation benefits, public works,\ni\nBring This Ad for $5\nOff All Repairs Over $50\nJACK GRIMES\nAutomotive Service, Inc.\n946 Eleanor at Lewis\nAUTOMATIC\nTRANSMISSION\nSPECIALISTS\nincreased social security bene\nfits and a higher minimum wage.\nADA Warns\nA\nAgainst Tying\nLabor\u2019s Hands\nCongressional leaders have a\nI \u201cgrowing awareness\u201d that prob\nlems of labor corruption will not\nbe solved by anti-labor panaceas,\na resolution on a strong, demo\ncratic labor movement adopted\nby Americans for Democratic\nAction declared.\n\u201cThose who for years have\nsought to place shackles on the\nlabor movement must not now\nbe permitted to accomplish their\npurposes with false and mislead\ning slogans\u2014'right-to-work'. 'la\nbor monopoly,' \u2018polal power\nof labor bosses.\u2019\",\u201d resolution\napproved by the\nnual convention s\n11th an-\"\nCommenting\nIan committee\nne McClel\nearings, the\nresolution said that \"organized\nlabor demonstrated its capa\ncity for self-correction when\nit drove Communist-domi\nnated unions from its ranks\nand when the AFL-CIO insti\ntuted quick and resolute ac\ntion to eliminate corruption.\u201d\nIt added that the \"future ef\nfectiveness\u201d of the committee\n\u201cdepends upon strict adher\nence to fair rules.\u201d\nSen. Paul H. Douglas (D-Ill.)\nin a speech to the convention\nbanquet called for an immediate\ntax cut of $6 billion and pro\nposed repeal or reduction of ex\ncise taxes. He said he would ex\npect \u201cthe automobile manufac\nturers would add a price reduc\ntion of their own to stimulate\nsales and employment.\u201d\nHumphrey Blasts Dulles\nSpeaking also at the banquet\ndinner. Sen. Hubert H. Humph\nrey (D-Minn.) warned that the\n\u201copposite of co-existence is no\nexistence\u201d and he said \u201cthe sta\ntus quo mentality\u201d of the Eisen\nhower-Dulles Administration is\nstrengthening the Communist\nbloc and weakening the United\nStates.\nRobert R. Nathan, Washington\nconsulting economist,\nwas\nre\nelected national Chairman of\nADA. Hayes, Lewis, Phillips and\nCarey were among those\nre\nelected members of the board,\nas were Walter P. Reuther,\nDavid Dubinsky and James G.\nPatton, Joseph E. Beirne, L. S.\nBuckmaster, O. A. Knight, B. F.\nMcLaurin and W. P. Kennedy.\nGIVE\nYOURSELF\nA GOOD\nBRAKE\nBy The\nExperts\nTURNER\nBRAKE SERVICE\nlll-14th St. CH. 3-8255\nC\nAL EDWARDS\u2019\nWheel Alignment\nFront End Rebuilding\nWheel Balancing and\nBrake Service\n2136 MONROE\nCH 1-3345\nPlanning Your Vacation? Let Us Help You\n8271 Ashland Avenue\nCH. 1-4142\nTOLEDO AUTO CLUB\nTravel Bureau 8:30 to 5 Daily\nReconditioned and Guaranteed\n\nPOWER\ne\nMOWERS\n$200\nCENTURY POWER MOWER\n4409 BENNETT near SPICER MFC.","height":"26868","width":"19480"}}
